abstract: WASHINGTON, Nov. 9--The unexpectedly strong performance by Republican candidates for the House and Senate in last Tuesday's election is expected to result in legislation reflecting more pro-business, anti-Government attitudes on spending, according to Congressional officials.

abstract: Back when I was a 10-year-old architecture critic, there wasn't much to do except play with blocks. Except for the story of Mike Mulligan and his trusty old steam shovel, Mary Ann, most books seemed to be about circuses and monkeys and baseball and cars. There wasn't much to read about buildings at all.

abstract: WASHINGTON--Congress wades into its lame duck session this week with more lame ducks in the pond than at any time since 1948. Eighteen Senators casting votes this week will not be back when the 97th Congress convenes in January, with Republicans in control for the first time in 26 years. Democrats retain a majority in the House, but there will be 71 new faces in 1981.
